Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[_Mycoplasma gallisepticum_ is an economically significant pathogen that can cause significant losses in chickens, turkeys, and game birds from chronic respiratory disease, reduced feed efficiency, decreased growth, and lower egg production. In addition, the carcasses of birds sent to slaughter may be downgraded. Many countries with modern poultry operations have eradicated this organism from commercial chicken and turkey breeding flocks; however, it can still be an issue in other poultry operations, such as multi-age layer flocks, game bird raising facilities, and backyard birds.

Since 1994, conjunctivitis caused by one lineage of _M. gallisepticum_ has become a significant disease in wild birds in North America. Although other wild birds can be affected, the major impact has been on house finches (_Carpodacus mexicanus_), which have experienced major population declines in some areas.

_M. gallisepticum_ can be found worldwide in poultry.

There is no evidence that _Mycoplasma gallisepticum_ is zoonotic.
Source: http://www.cfsph.iastate.edu/Factsheets/pdfs/avian_mycoplasmosis_mycoplasma_gallisepticum.pdf. - Mod.CRD

